I finally understand your confusion; The feature that is broken is "ARRAY_AT": this is a vendor specific extension of the standard that was introduced to simplify porting existing code to 4diac;

What this allows is:
If you have e.g. a DWORD variable you can define a "reference" to this variable which allows to access parts of this variable using the array-index notation in Structured Text, on the ST-side this would look like

  VAR
    myVariable : DWORD;
    myReferenceToTheVariable : ARRAY [0..31] OF BOOL AT myVariable;
  END_VAR;
  myReferenceToTheVariable[5] := false; //this will set a single bit

On the C++-side this is not implemented using the index operator but rather through a templated method that can be optimized away.

In short: the object that is accessed is no array on the c++ side

Patch Set 3:

I think using ConcurrentHashMap would only work if it had a method that replaced all entries in an atomic operation. Just using ConcurrentHashMap can result in race conditions where #getChildren()/#getElements() return incomplete results while #update() is incrementally altering the map.

We could also use a read/write instead lock instead of synchronizing the #update method, instantiating a new map on each update and using volatile field access.

Patch Set 3:

For some reason I cannot reply to your code-inline comments. My comments are always marked as draft and the "Reply" butto is missing.

So I respond here:

The current code that tries to handle DocumentSymbolWithFile or DocumentSymbol in getParent() is effectively dead code, as the SymbolsModel#parent HashMap that is used for lookup is always empty. So calling getParent() with a DocumentSymbolWithFile or DocumentSymbol will always return null.

Thus I removed the dead code.

Patch Set 3:

> For some reason I cannot reply to your code-inline comments. My comments are always marked as draft and the "Reply" butto is missing.

They're first added as draft and then you have to use the regular "Reply" dialog for general comment and use Send. The "drafts" comments inline gets incorporated in the reply.

> The current code that tries to handle DocumentSymbolWithFile or DocumentSymbol in getParent() is effectively dead code, as the SymbolsModel#parent HashMap that is used for lookup is always empty.

OK, so shouldn't we remove this map by the way? And have you tried with multiple language servers? There are older LS that may still use other types, so this may be dead code in many cases, but not all.
So it seems safer to keep this code for the moment, particularly if it doesn't really participate in the fix.

How are users of the JGit API going to hold on to this RefDatabase so that they get the caching?

The JGit API is not thread-safe, so we can't keep a repo open and reuse it across requests.

> 

> The JGit API is not thread-safe, so we can't keep a repo open and reuse it across requests.

I think we can? We just can't use it from two threads simultaneously.

Also, the threading characteristics are different between DfsRefDatabase and RefDirectory. I see locks and atomics in the latter, which suggests thread-safety.

Patch Set 4:

> We just can't use it from two threads simultaneously.

So it's not thread-safe :-)

> Also, the threading characteristics are different between DfsRefDatabase and RefDirectory.

That's one more argument why it's not thread-safe and we can't just pass open repos around. IMO: Either the API and it's implementations guarantee that or they don't and I think they don't today and it would be a larger effort to make it so (please correct me).

Making the whole API thread safe just from the outside is not feasible IMO, that would have to happen from code changes within the implementations.

However, I think we might be able to solve this by passing in just a shared RefCache instance when opening a repo, making that thread-safe and have callers hold onto that as they want. WDYT?
